<v Expert1>Let's engage with
disabled people about what

00:00:03.679 --> 00:00:05.000
we are going to do for them.

00:00:05.020 --> 00:00:08.850
<v Expert2>We must remember to ensure
everyone is consulted, including a

00:00:08.850 --> 00:00:10.810
small percentage of disabled people.

00:00:10.850 --> 00:00:13.000
It's fine for others to
speak on their behalf.

00:00:13.379 --> 00:00:16.630
<v Jonathan>No, way, let's
disrupt the disability discourse.

00:00:17.039 --> 00:00:20.119
It's the Disability
Disrupters Podcast with Dr.

00:00:20.150 --> 00:00:21.020
Pam MacNeill.

00:00:21.698 --> 00:00:24.578
<v Dr Pam>Greetings everyone, and
welcome to February's edition of

00:00:24.578 --> 00:00:26.918
the Disability Disrupters podcast.

00:00:27.338 --> 00:00:32.768
Today's guest is Kylee Maloney,
former broadcaster, current fan

00:00:32.768 --> 00:00:34.568
fiction writer, and Gym Bunny.

00:00:35.048 --> 00:00:37.208
Kylee's interview is not to be missed.

00:00:37.708 --> 00:00:41.068
Remember, if you know someone you think
we should interview or you just wanna

00:00:41.068 --> 00:00:42.931
get in touch, we'd love to hear from you.

00:00:43.351 --> 00:00:50.306
Send an email to disrupters@drnz.co.nz
with your thoughts on

00:00:50.306 --> 00:00:52.196
disability related topics.

00:00:52.526 --> 00:00:54.356
We look forward to hearing from you.

00:00:55.226 --> 00:00:57.836
now, sit back, relax, and
enjoy this month's show.

00:01:05.998 --> 00:01:12.178
You are involved with the Royal New
Zealand Foundation for the Blind Redress

00:01:12.178 --> 00:01:18.538
Group, as am I. But I want to talk to you
about the group from your perspective,

00:01:19.078 --> 00:01:22.138
how things have tracked, how it all began.

00:01:22.648 --> 00:01:25.993
If you can basically let people
know, because I think that around

00:01:25.993 --> 00:01:31.153
the world there are a lot of people
who are in a similar Situation.

00:01:31.303 --> 00:01:36.163
There have perhaps been royal commissions
of inquiry or other types of inquiries

00:01:36.223 --> 00:01:41.983
into abuse in the care of the state or
church, and I think that from a disability

00:01:41.983 --> 00:01:43.658
perspective, this one's a bit unusual.

00:01:45.043 --> 00:01:49.093
<v Kylee>Yes it is, because,
I think for the first time a

00:01:49.093 --> 00:01:55.908
charity has allowed a group of
survivors to call the tune really.

00:01:56.628 --> 00:02:00.528
And that is unusual, especially
for a disability organization.

00:02:01.248 --> 00:02:05.688
For me, it started, I was one of the
people profiled in the commission.

00:02:05.738 --> 00:02:09.318
The report has a number
of case histories in it.

00:02:09.318 --> 00:02:10.098
Mine was one of them.

00:02:11.118 --> 00:02:16.698
And then after it was released, the
then chair of the board issued an email,

00:02:16.698 --> 00:02:19.368
which looked to me like all but denial.

00:02:20.748 --> 00:02:23.998
So I contacted the  chief
executive as I know you did.

00:02:24.498 --> 00:02:29.328
And she formed this group out of people
who had contacted her or people who

00:02:29.328 --> 00:02:32.058
she had found through other means.

00:02:32.358 --> 00:02:34.403
And that's basically how it started.

00:02:34.433 --> 00:02:40.033
She wanted people, to get together,
survivors who could move the thing

00:02:40.033 --> 00:02:43.628
forward, who could co-design an
apology, which we did over a year.

00:02:43.963 --> 00:02:45.823
That was a lot of back and forth email.

00:02:47.188 --> 00:02:50.578
Wrangling over words
because words are important.

00:02:51.478 --> 00:02:56.248
And the apology happened on the 18th of
September by this time where our group

00:02:56.248 --> 00:03:01.438
had been formed and we'd already started,
and now we are working on a framework for

00:03:01.438 --> 00:03:05.338
compensation and redress, which is huge.

00:03:05.368 --> 00:03:07.018
I've never done anything like this before.

00:03:07.018 --> 00:03:09.058
I do the admin basically.

00:03:09.058 --> 00:03:14.188
I set up the Zoom meetings and do the
minutes and things like that, but, and

00:03:14.188 --> 00:03:17.988
also provide some wordsmithing, we all
play to our strengths and I think that's

00:03:17.988 --> 00:03:19.308
what's really good about this group.

00:03:19.308 --> 00:03:22.278
There's only four of us, but
we all have different strengths

00:03:22.398 --> 00:03:23.748
and we're all complimentary.

00:03:23.748 --> 00:03:28.598
I don't think I've ever worked
with such a cohesive group.

00:03:29.598 --> 00:03:33.578
<v Dr Pam>That's right and as you say,
the apology was last year in September

00:03:33.858 --> 00:03:39.193
and since then we've been busy putting
together a framework and timeline.

00:03:39.193 --> 00:03:43.333
We've got two years to basically
do this task and it's not quite

00:03:43.333 --> 00:03:44.743
as easy as you would think, is

00:03:44.743 --> 00:03:47.948
it because, as you say, all the
wordsmithing we've had to do?

00:03:49.003 --> 00:03:54.813
<v Kylee>It's a huge job and really
does involve all of our skills.

00:03:54.813 --> 00:03:55.683
All four of us.

00:03:55.683 --> 00:03:59.103
We've all got different skills
that we contribute, and it really

00:03:59.103 --> 00:04:00.813
does involve all of them, I think

00:04:01.563 --> 00:04:03.813
more than even we suspected.

00:04:03.843 --> 00:04:05.913
But at the moment, things are going well.

00:04:05.913 --> 00:04:13.633
We are tracking well, and I think we're
on target to produce our document at

00:04:13.633 --> 00:04:18.043
the board meeting in March, so that'll
be exciting to see how they receive it.

00:04:18.673 --> 00:04:19.003
<v Dr Pam>yes.

00:04:19.003 --> 00:04:19.243
And then

00:04:19.243 --> 00:04:24.133
we can start working on applications
and we really keen to hear from anyone

00:04:24.223 --> 00:04:26.053
who feels that they were impacted,

00:04:26.413 --> 00:04:30.558
anyone who's blind or low vision or deaf
blind, who feels they were impacted.

00:04:31.108 --> 00:04:32.278
Needs to get in touch.

00:04:32.278 --> 00:04:35.638
I, I'll leave Steffie's email address.

00:04:35.638 --> 00:04:39.688
Steffie Birkhead is our first
contact person and I'll leave

00:04:39.688 --> 00:04:43.898
her address and other information
about the group in the show notes.

00:04:44.248 --> 00:04:45.928
But just to profile who we are.

00:04:45.928 --> 00:04:51.598
There's you, Kylee, there's
Dr. Don McLaren from Geraldine.

00:04:51.648 --> 00:04:53.428
So Geraldine in the South Island.

00:04:53.858 --> 00:04:58.598
There's Steffie Birkhead
who lives in, remind me,

00:04:58.818 --> 00:05:00.518
<v Kylee>In Missouri in the USA.

00:05:00.658 --> 00:05:02.738
<v Dr Pam>Not Misery, Missouri

00:05:03.103 --> 00:05:05.803
Although actually I think their
weather's been pretty bad, so maybe

00:05:05.803 --> 00:05:07.303
she does live in Misery at the moment.

00:05:07.853 --> 00:05:09.773
But yeah, so there's four of us.

00:05:09.773 --> 00:05:14.543
I'm chairing, but we've all got equal
participation and equal responsibility.

00:05:14.543 --> 00:05:18.168
It's just as you said, so
well, a question of people.

00:05:19.433 --> 00:05:22.793
Playing to their strengths, and we
communicate directly to the chief

00:05:22.793 --> 00:05:25.223
executive at Blind and Low Vision.

00:05:25.613 --> 00:05:27.833
So it's a bit complicated, isn't it?

00:05:27.893 --> 00:05:31.083
Kylee, do you wanna unpick that
whole thing of, we're talking about

00:05:31.083 --> 00:05:35.073
the Royal New Zealand Foundation for
the Blind on the one hand and then

00:05:35.073 --> 00:05:36.603
blind and low vision on the other

00:05:36.603 --> 00:05:39.393
<v Kylee>it was Royal New Zealand
Foundation for the Blind until,

00:05:39.393 --> 00:05:41.253
what, 2001 or something like that?

00:05:41.643 --> 00:05:42.453
<v Dr Pam>something like that.

00:05:42.453 --> 00:05:42.753
Yep.

00:05:43.228 --> 00:05:48.073
<v Kylee>When it changed to of the blind
because we it, the, it used to be governed

00:05:48.073 --> 00:05:51.613
by an act of Parliament and of course
the royal means it has a Royal warrant.

00:05:52.603 --> 00:05:56.053
The organization is still Royal New
Zealand Foundation of the Blind.

00:05:56.053 --> 00:05:57.583
That's its legal name

00:05:57.863 --> 00:06:01.283
It's still has its Royal Warrant,
but the brand name, the business name

00:06:01.733 --> 00:06:03.773
that it uses is Blind Low Vision nz.

00:06:04.323 --> 00:06:05.673
<v Dr Pam>That was very well put.

00:06:05.913 --> 00:06:10.083
So if anyone was confused, hopefully
that's cleared up your confusion.

00:06:10.583 --> 00:06:13.253
We've got a meeting coming
up shortly, actually.

00:06:13.253 --> 00:06:14.513
So we are meeting once a month.

00:06:14.513 --> 00:06:16.493
We're sometimes meeting
twice a month, aren't we?

00:06:17.153 --> 00:06:20.248
<v Kylee>Yeah, occasionally we meet
twice a month, but  our next meeting

00:06:20.248 --> 00:06:23.738
is coming up where we'll bring together
a lot of the strands that we've all

00:06:23.738 --> 00:06:30.518
been working on for this document and
application process, which has been quite

00:06:31.508 --> 00:06:33.368
exciting to see it coming together really.

00:06:33.368 --> 00:06:35.908
But yes, a huge amount of work for all of

00:06:35.998 --> 00:06:37.738
<v Dr Pam>Lots and lots of emails.

00:06:37.738 --> 00:06:39.898
So obviously we've got
a group that we set up.

00:06:39.898 --> 00:06:44.653
We've got a Dropbox folder, etc. So
if anybody's thinking of starting

00:06:44.653 --> 00:06:48.133
anything similar to this drop us a
line 'cause I'm sure we can probably

00:06:48.133 --> 00:06:51.063
advise people on the pitfalls and
the good things about doing it.

00:06:51.893 --> 00:06:57.703
Kylee, do you want to move on and tell
people a bit more about you, who you are?

00:06:59.928 --> 00:07:02.178
Because you've got a
really brilliant history

00:07:02.238 --> 00:07:02.868
and you

00:07:02.868 --> 00:07:06.508
do brilliant things with with
your fiction and things like that.

00:07:07.008 --> 00:07:07.368
<v Kylee>Thank you.

00:07:07.368 --> 00:07:07.938
I'm well.

00:07:07.943 --> 00:07:09.548
I'm a Celt by heritage.

00:07:09.548 --> 00:07:14.558
The one, one thing I have a problem with
is being lumped into the whole European

00:07:14.558 --> 00:07:21.728
category of New Zealander, because
European has such a wide cultural mix.

00:07:22.208 --> 00:07:24.038
It's not specific enough for me.

00:07:24.038 --> 00:07:28.498
I'm a Celtic New Zealander because  I had
four great grandparents who were Irish

00:07:28.498 --> 00:07:30.778
out of eight, two Welsh and two Scottish.

00:07:30.808 --> 00:07:32.188
So there we are.

00:07:34.688 --> 00:07:37.778
But I went to Homai, for all
of my schooling, I was probably

00:07:37.778 --> 00:07:39.068
one of the last to do that.

00:07:39.068 --> 00:07:42.008
A lot of the kids were
mainstreamed, at least to high

00:07:42.008 --> 00:07:43.988
school by the time I came along.

00:07:43.988 --> 00:07:49.088
But I was one of the last to go
full term from age five to 19.

00:07:49.908 --> 00:07:51.488
<v Dr Pam>It's a long time Kylee.

00:07:51.698 --> 00:07:53.288
<v Kylee>Yes, it is.

00:07:53.288 --> 00:07:55.988
It's a long chunk out of
someone's life and I'm only now

00:07:55.988 --> 00:07:58.838
realizing what impact that had.

00:08:00.098 --> 00:08:04.928
And it's not just realizing, it's
making yourself realize it because

00:08:05.928 --> 00:08:07.968
it's difficult and it's easy to avoid.

00:08:07.968 --> 00:08:11.808
And one thing that I'm learning is
that most human beings are avoidant.

00:08:12.078 --> 00:08:16.488
We tend to not want to know the
dark side of ourselves, the shadow

00:08:16.488 --> 00:08:18.228
self, I think Jung calls it.

00:08:18.978 --> 00:08:21.378
And we tend to avoid those
things because they're difficult.

00:08:21.378 --> 00:08:24.888
We don't wanna see them, we don't
want it to reflect badly on us, or

00:08:24.938 --> 00:08:29.768
we think it will, but it's important
because self-knowledge is a gift.

00:08:29.813 --> 00:08:29.873
Yeah.

00:08:30.443 --> 00:08:33.633
Once you start knowing yourself, you
start knowing, your fellow human beings

00:08:33.653 --> 00:08:39.203
better, but you have to make yourself
go through that because you can't go

00:08:39.203 --> 00:08:43.103
around, you can't ignore it because it
just becomes baggage you keep carrying.

00:08:43.373 --> 00:08:44.933
So the only way is through.

00:08:45.293 --> 00:08:47.963
It's the hardest way, but it's
really the only way that works.

00:08:49.913 --> 00:08:57.973
Anyway, I went to Homai and I tried to be
successful in wider society with moderate

00:08:58.513 --> 00:09:03.403
and sporadic successes, and I've only
recently found out why that was too.

00:09:03.403 --> 00:09:09.293
But I started in the public sector
as a typist because I like words.

00:09:09.293 --> 00:09:13.273
I've always been a word sort of a
words are one of my big interests.

00:09:14.563 --> 00:09:17.113
But typing was just
easy  But not copy typing.

00:09:17.293 --> 00:09:21.733
Typing other people's piffle without being
able to correct their grammar was torture.

00:09:22.783 --> 00:09:23.973
<v Dr Pam>It would be

00:09:24.258 --> 00:09:25.008
<v Kylee>it was.

00:09:25.548 --> 00:09:28.518
But the medical typing where I started
actually was the most interesting

00:09:28.518 --> 00:09:31.948
because I had work experience at
Palmie Hospital and that was fun.

00:09:31.988 --> 00:09:34.868
I learned something all
the time while I was there.

00:09:34.908 --> 00:09:39.258
Every time I typed something new, some
different medical discipline, I remember

00:09:39.258 --> 00:09:41.048
once yelling across  the typing pool.

00:09:41.198 --> 00:09:42.968
How do you spell tachycardia?

00:09:43.088 --> 00:09:45.968
And this voice in my
ear spelled it for me.

00:09:45.968 --> 00:09:48.548
And it turned around and there
was the head of coronary care.

00:09:54.348 --> 00:09:57.768
So I got interested in equal employment
opportunities while I was at social

00:09:57.768 --> 00:10:03.663
welfare, because that was my first
paid typing job and it was then that

00:10:03.663 --> 00:10:07.473
I started getting interested in the
disability activism side of things.

00:10:07.743 --> 00:10:11.553
I was never very, what you'd call active,
but I was always interested in learning.

00:10:12.063 --> 00:10:20.313
So I was, I represented our office in EEO
for the time I was there, and then I got a

00:10:20.313 --> 00:10:25.923
job as the Northern Regional Administrator
of the mainstream program, and that's

00:10:25.923 --> 00:10:28.323
where I first came to work under you.

00:10:28.533 --> 00:10:30.453
Because you took over
from Mike Goy, didn't you?

00:10:30.453 --> 00:10:33.783
So you became my boss and we
worked together for a while.

00:10:33.853 --> 00:10:36.733
We had met at Homai before that
When you had your first dog,

00:10:36.988 --> 00:10:37.663
<v Dr Pam>Oh, that's right.

00:10:38.023 --> 00:10:38.293
Yeah.

00:10:38.603 --> 00:10:40.583
And our starts were
actually really similar,

00:10:40.583 --> 00:10:42.413
both being at social welfare, et cetera.

00:10:42.683 --> 00:10:43.193
<v Kylee>yes.

00:10:43.223 --> 00:10:43.553
Yeah.

00:10:44.693 --> 00:10:50.273
So I then moved from State Services
Commission when it had, its in

00:10:50.273 --> 00:10:52.913
terminable, restructures 'cause it
was always having those back then.

00:10:53.033 --> 00:10:53.483
<v Dr Pam>Yes.

00:10:53.898 --> 00:10:54.173
Yes, indeed.

00:10:55.628 --> 00:10:58.438
<v Kylee>I moved to the employment
service, which was very exciting,

00:10:58.438 --> 00:11:02.938
very stressful, but it cost me
a lot in terms of my resources.

00:11:03.628 --> 00:11:04.498
I did well at it.

00:11:04.498 --> 00:11:05.338
I enjoyed it.

00:11:05.438 --> 00:11:08.768
I was the person who came in to see
when you looked on the board for a

00:11:08.768 --> 00:11:11.978
job and you then lined up and went to
see one of the people in the cubicles.

00:11:12.158 --> 00:11:17.618
I was one of those back in the
nineties, which was very interesting.

00:11:17.618 --> 00:11:20.938
It was interesting to meet
so many different people with

00:11:20.938 --> 00:11:22.348
so many different skills.

00:11:23.248 --> 00:11:29.278
I first noticed racism when I was
there because we had some foreign

00:11:29.648 --> 00:11:34.628
people who were quite well qualified,
but we couldn't get them jobs.

00:11:36.008 --> 00:11:40.358
And it was my first time that I actually
noticed that sort of thing that outside

00:11:40.408 --> 00:11:45.088
the disability sector, and it just was
something that never made sense to me.

00:11:45.088 --> 00:11:49.113
I remember we had one guy who was
stainless steel qualified, in metal work.

00:11:49.113 --> 00:11:51.958
And it was really difficult to
get people who were qualified in

00:11:51.958 --> 00:11:53.938
stainless steel, but he was Moroccan.

00:11:53.938 --> 00:11:54.868
And do you think we could get it?

00:11:54.958 --> 00:11:56.578
Oh, it was very frustrating.

00:11:56.938 --> 00:11:57.328
Yeah.

00:11:57.868 --> 00:12:03.618
But so I had a burnout and
I left work after that.

00:12:04.548 --> 00:12:07.638
I now know what that probably was.

00:12:07.668 --> 00:12:11.028
At the time we thought it was
just depression, but depression's

00:12:11.028 --> 00:12:13.668
just a side issue for me, really.

00:12:16.468 --> 00:12:19.318
Because the main cause was my autism.

00:12:19.648 --> 00:12:24.658
So I just found out I'm
autistic last August.

00:12:24.748 --> 00:12:25.613
But we'll get to that.

00:12:26.243 --> 00:12:31.713
So I drifted for a while, but I'd made
an album in 1998 and that was equally

00:12:31.713 --> 00:12:35.588
exciting and stressful because music
had always been a part of the culture

00:12:35.588 --> 00:12:40.208
at Homai, you had to do music in some
form, and especially in the girls

00:12:40.208 --> 00:12:45.728
hostel where I grew up, we were always
singing, harmonizing, collaborating

00:12:45.733 --> 00:12:47.288
on music, all that sort of thing.

00:12:47.338 --> 00:12:49.173
<v Dr Pam>What was the
name of your album, Kylee?

00:12:49.193 --> 00:12:50.813
In case people want to have a listen,

00:12:51.008 --> 00:12:52.508
<v Kylee>it was called First Light.

00:12:52.508 --> 00:12:54.698
Now , there's a cut
down version on Spotify.

00:12:54.698 --> 00:12:57.758
I'm not quite sure what it's called,
but if you look for my name on

00:12:57.758 --> 00:12:59.378
Spotify, you probably will find

00:12:59.443 --> 00:13:01.663
<v Dr Pam>We'll find a way
to exit the interview with a

00:13:01.663 --> 00:13:03.103
track if that's okay with you.

00:13:03.498 --> 00:13:04.453
<v Kylee>Yeah, that's fine.

00:13:04.588 --> 00:13:05.608
I can send you a track.

00:13:05.608 --> 00:13:09.008
So yes that was very exciting.

00:13:09.008 --> 00:13:13.078
Although I learned a lot, I learned
how naive I was for a start because

00:13:13.198 --> 00:13:17.548
the distribution was all taken
over by Warners who didn't actually

00:13:17.698 --> 00:13:22.078
participate in the album, but they
got the distribution rights and the

00:13:22.078 --> 00:13:23.158
album actually doesn't belong to me.

00:13:23.158 --> 00:13:24.508
It belongs to Frontier Records.

00:13:25.018 --> 00:13:27.268
So yes, it's all

00:13:27.283 --> 00:13:28.408
<v Dr Pam>But you still get royalties.

00:13:29.038 --> 00:13:31.208
<v Kylee>oh no, it's
all very complicated.

00:13:31.208 --> 00:13:33.908
I think if I did it again,
I'd do it myself because I

00:13:33.908 --> 00:13:35.348
learned to be a broadcaster.

00:13:35.348 --> 00:13:41.778
After that, I went to a school in Porirua
and I was hired by Radio New Zealand

00:13:41.868 --> 00:13:47.098
on the mainstream program again this
time as a spoken features producer.

00:13:47.128 --> 00:13:51.718
And my job was to be a co-presenter
for the one in five program, which

00:13:51.718 --> 00:13:55.978
was on disability on Sunday nights, on
national radio as it was called then.

00:13:56.533 --> 00:13:57.573
<v Dr Pam>Absolutely awesome at it.

00:13:57.748 --> 00:13:58.348
<v Kylee>Oh, thank you.

00:13:58.588 --> 00:14:00.028
It was something I did enjoy.

00:14:01.228 --> 00:14:03.988
It was also a very toxic
