worship him, and I do mean that.

00:27:19.028 --> 00:27:22.988
Back in the early naughties I found
out there was a live journal group of

00:27:22.988 --> 00:27:28.598
mainly middle-aged women who called
themselves Snapeists or Snape wives.

00:27:29.528 --> 00:27:32.558
They treated him as their master.

00:27:32.558 --> 00:27:36.758
They would hold fantasy weddings with him.

00:27:36.968 --> 00:27:39.848
The whole thing, it really was a religion.

00:27:40.343 --> 00:27:43.283
<v Dr Pam>Imagine AI
now inject AI into that,

00:27:43.343 --> 00:27:47.063
and then you've got this real whole
ecosystem happening that could be.

00:27:48.773 --> 00:27:49.823
<v Kylee>It is dangerous.

00:27:49.823 --> 00:27:56.303
Even in YouTube now, there are all these
fantasy, they're very well done, but a

00:27:56.303 --> 00:28:00.638
lot of them are on Snape being and I think
Alan Rickman's portrayal in the movies

00:28:00.828 --> 00:28:06.258
has had a lot to do with this, and I'm
sure the late great Alan Rickman would

00:28:06.258 --> 00:28:10.578
be horrified because from what I read
about him, he was a highly principled man.

00:28:10.908 --> 00:28:14.988
I'm sure he would be horrified
to think that his voice, would be

00:28:14.988 --> 00:28:20.673
turned into AI and used for this
unhealthily, oh, man, possessing

00:28:20.678 --> 00:28:23.528
a woman type style of production.

00:28:23.768 --> 00:28:29.048
But YouTube, it's all over
YouTube, but the stories that I

00:28:29.048 --> 00:28:32.828
write are about redemption because
I don't think he was redeemed.

00:28:32.828 --> 00:28:34.298
I think the potential was there.

00:28:35.813 --> 00:28:38.243
So that's what made me sad
when he was killed off.

00:28:38.293 --> 00:28:44.023
Not that because he was redeemed by his
love of Lily, but the potential was there.

00:28:45.373 --> 00:28:49.693
And so I thought I wonder what
would happen if we worked on

00:28:49.693 --> 00:28:52.393
that potential, because that, for
me, that changes the narrative.

00:28:52.633 --> 00:28:57.423
I can't talk to this matron or my other
abusers to ask them why they did what

00:28:57.423 --> 00:28:59.853
they did, but this is what I can do.

00:29:01.413 --> 00:29:03.933
So it's, it becomes a
healthy thing for me.

00:29:04.263 --> 00:29:04.683
<v Dr Pam>yes.

00:29:05.283 --> 00:29:07.113
<v Kylee>A way of
working through issues.

00:29:07.383 --> 00:29:08.313
<v Dr Pam>really well put.

00:29:08.553 --> 00:29:08.853
Yeah.

00:29:09.813 --> 00:29:14.583
And so you brought us full circle to
something else I wanted to ask you

00:29:14.583 --> 00:29:16.433
about, which was you're a gym bunny.

00:29:17.483 --> 00:29:22.433
<v Kylee>Yes, I, P.E. Was
a nightmare for me at Homai.

00:29:22.458 --> 00:29:28.418
I couldn't do most of the things
my proprioception is not great.

00:29:29.108 --> 00:29:33.253
Part of autism I now have discovered
and in my interception as well.

00:29:33.613 --> 00:29:36.523
So my body will tell me things even
though my mind isn't telling me.

00:29:36.523 --> 00:29:40.513
So if I'm stressed, my body will react
in a certain way, even if I don't

00:29:41.383 --> 00:29:45.043
acknowledge that I feel stressed or
that I don't notice things like that.

00:29:45.043 --> 00:29:50.623
And there's a disconnect, but we were,
running athletics 'cause that was the

00:29:50.623 --> 00:29:53.973
focus of our pe if it wasn't in games.

00:29:54.993 --> 00:29:57.393
But the one thing we never
did was weightlifting.

00:29:57.453 --> 00:29:59.973
And it's the one thing
I found I'm good at.

00:30:00.273 --> 00:30:01.173
I'm built for it.

00:30:01.173 --> 00:30:03.483
I'm short, I'm in proportion.

00:30:03.963 --> 00:30:05.883
And I love lifting.

00:30:06.043 --> 00:30:10.543
It's mainly on machines now, but I've
just started seriously getting into the

00:30:10.543 --> 00:30:16.963
power lifting, which is three disciplines,
deadlift, bench press, and squat.

00:30:17.683 --> 00:30:20.533
<v Dr Pam>So do you do that thing,
I think it might be the bench press.

00:30:20.533 --> 00:30:24.823
Do you do that thing where you lie on
your back and then you've got to get the

00:30:24.823 --> 00:30:27.463
weight and push it up towards the ceiling?

00:30:27.763 --> 00:30:29.023
<v Kylee>Yes, that's the bench press.

00:30:29.083 --> 00:30:33.453
<v Dr Pam>I can't do, because
I lose all my sense of where

00:30:33.453 --> 00:30:36.513
things are and I wobble and I'm
not sure where the ceiling is.

00:30:36.513 --> 00:30:40.473
It's quite when I've got heavy weights
in my head because I've got excuses now.

00:30:40.473 --> 00:30:41.763
Having broken my wrist

00:30:42.183 --> 00:30:44.218
Last year I just can't do that.

00:30:44.278 --> 00:30:47.998
And the other thing I can't do is
squat because I have chronic sciatica.

00:30:48.208 --> 00:30:48.328
And

00:30:48.358 --> 00:30:52.438
I'll tell you honestly, I don't
miss not being able to do squat.

00:30:52.798 --> 00:30:53.548
They're awful.

00:30:54.898 --> 00:30:55.348
But you do.

00:30:55.423 --> 00:30:57.733
<v Kylee>I had, yeah, I enjoy it.

00:30:57.943 --> 00:31:00.943
I can get up off the floor without
help, quite happily still, which,

00:31:01.043 --> 00:31:02.813
not everyone my age can do that.

00:31:02.843 --> 00:31:07.033
Apparently I hold the female record
in the gym, it's therapeutic because

00:31:07.573 --> 00:31:11.293
it's about overlaying negative
memories with positive ones.

00:31:11.483 --> 00:31:11.703
<v Dr Pam>Yes.

00:31:12.488 --> 00:31:15.778
<v Kylee>That's what all this is about
for me now in this time of my life.

00:31:16.278 --> 00:31:17.688
<v Dr Pam>Just sounds really awesome.

00:31:17.688 --> 00:31:22.228
And I think a lot of people listening
are going to be thinking, wow, it's

00:31:22.228 --> 00:31:26.788
good to have role models who can do
that, who can find their ways through

00:31:27.358 --> 00:31:32.338
a forest of, often very negative
experiences, but come out the other

00:31:32.338 --> 00:31:36.638
side or at least begin doing that and
pass that knowledge and that wisdom on

00:31:37.138 --> 00:31:40.488
a lot of people wouldn't do that, so I
really thank you for doing that, Kylee.

00:31:40.988 --> 00:31:41.778
<v Kylee>It's my pleasure.

00:31:41.778 --> 00:31:43.158
It's something I enjoy.

00:31:43.218 --> 00:31:44.898
I enjoy passing on what I have.

00:31:45.138 --> 00:31:50.148
I enjoy being useful, but I actually
am so seldom allowed to be useful.

00:31:50.388 --> 00:31:51.018
So

00:31:51.558 --> 00:31:51.888
it's

00:31:52.053 --> 00:31:53.928
<v Dr Pam>we want you
in the disability sector.

00:31:53.928 --> 00:31:55.038
You could be very useful.

00:31:55.038 --> 00:31:55.638
I'm sure.

00:31:58.248 --> 00:31:58.758
<v Kylee>yes,

00:31:58.818 --> 00:32:01.128
<v Dr Pam>a role model and
lots of other things too.

00:32:01.128 --> 00:32:06.828
You've got lots of talents and I really
hope that you get further opportunities

00:32:06.828 --> 00:32:10.298
that you want and not the ones you
don't 'cause, sometimes we're offered

00:32:10.298 --> 00:32:12.968
things and we refuse them, and people
think we're awfully ungrateful.

00:32:13.298 --> 00:32:16.508
But if it's going to, as you say,
deplete your resources, there's

00:32:16.508 --> 00:32:17.798
no point in accepting those.

00:32:18.613 --> 00:32:19.103
<v Kylee>exactly.

